<p>
One of the stipulations in <xref ref="pro-lincombgeo"/> is that vectors <m>\mathbf{u}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m> should be non-collinear.  You can use the interactive in <xref ref="exp-proc4"/> to investigate what happens when <m>\mathbf{u}</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}</m> are collinear.  The following example examines what happens from a geometric as well as an algebraic standpoint.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-lincombgeometry2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Can the vector <m>[3,2]</m> be written as a linear combination of vectors <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m>?
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            We will start with a geometric approach.

<image width="80%">
   <shortdescription>Three vectors drawn</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
\draw[thin,gray!40] (-4,-5) grid (7,4);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-4,0)--(7,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-5)--(0,4);
  \draw[line width=2pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(-3,1) node[above right]{\(\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}\)};

 \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(6,-2) node[below left]{\(\begin{bmatrix}6\\-2\end{bmatrix}\)};

 \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth](0,0)--(3,2)node[right]{\(\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\end{bmatrix}\)}; 
 
    \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>


Observe that <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m> are scalar multiples of each other and lie on the same line.  

A linear combination of <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m> has the form:


<me>
    a\begin{bmatrix}6\\-2\end{bmatrix}+b\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}=a(-2)\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}+b\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}=(-2a+b)\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>


This shows that all linear combinations of <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m> 
will be scalar multiples of <m>[-3,1]</m>, and therefore lie on the same line as <m>[-3,1]</m>.
Since <m>[3,2]</m> does not lie on the line determined by <m>[-3,1]</m> 
it cannot be expressed as a linear combination of <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m>.

We can also address this question algebraically.  To express <m>[3,2]</m> as a linear combination of
 <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m>, we need to solve the equation.

<me>
    a\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}+b\begin{bmatrix}6\\-2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\2\end{bmatrix}
</me>

This gives us a system of equations
<md>
    <mrow> -3a+6b\amp =3 </mrow>
    <mrow> a-2b\amp =2 </mrow>
</md>

When you try to solve this system, you will find that the system is inconsistent.  
Thus, <m>[3,2]</m> cannot be written as a linear combination of <m>[-3,1]</m> and <m>[6,-2]</m>.

We know that there is no way to express <m>[3,2]</m> as a linear combination of vectors <m>[-3,1]</m> 
and <m>[6,-2]</m>.  What would happen if we tried to apply <xref ref="pro-lincombgeo"/> to these vectors?  
You can use the GeoGebra interactive in <xref ref="exp-proc4"/> to find out.
       </p>
    </answer>
</example>





<example xml:id="ex-lincombgeometry1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Express <m>[2,4]</m> as a linear combination of <m>[2,1]</m> and <m>[2,-2]</m>.  Interpret your results geometrically.
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            We need to find scalars <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that 

<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}2\\4\end{bmatrix}=a\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}+b\begin{bmatrix}2\\-2\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

This amounts to solving a system of linear equations
<md>
    <mrow> 2a+2b\amp =2 </mrow>
    <mrow> a-2b\amp =4 </mrow>
</md>
Use your favorite method to solve this system. (Hint: adding the second equation to the first will work well for this system.) You will find that <m>a=2</m> and <m>b=-1</m>.  
Now we can write <m>[2,4]</m> as a linear combination of <m>[2,1]</m> and <m>[2,-2]</m> as follows:


<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}2\\4\end{bmatrix}=2\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}+(-1)\begin{bmatrix}2\\-2\end{bmatrix}.
</me>


Geometrically speaking, this means that the  <m>[2,4]</m> is the diagonal of the parallelogram determined by <m>2[2,1]</m> 
and <m>(-1) [2,-2]</m>.  
</p> 

<p> 
The original vectors <m>[2,1]</m> and <m>[2,-2]</m> are shown below together with the parallelogram and its diagonal. 
</p>

<image width="90%">
   <shortdescription>Paralellogram with diagonal drawn</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
\draw[thin,gray!40] (-4,-4) grid (4,4);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (-4,0)--(4,0);
  \draw[\lt -\gt ] (0,-4)--(0,4);
  
  \filldraw[blue, opacity=0.3](0,0)--(-2,2)--(2,4)--(4,2)--cycle;
\draw[line width=2pt,red,-stealth](0,0)--(2,1) node[below right]{\(\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}\)};
\draw[line width=2pt,red,-stealth, dashed](0,0)--(4,2) node[below right]{\(2\begin{bmatrix}2\\1\end{bmatrix}\)};

 \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth](0,0)--(2,-2) node[right]{\(\begin{bmatrix}2\\-2\end{bmatrix}\)};
 \draw[line width=2pt,blue,-stealth, dashed](0,0)--(-2,2) node[above left]{\((-1)\begin{bmatrix}2\\-2\end{bmatrix}\)};
 \draw[line width=2pt,-stealth](0,0)--(2,4); 
    \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>

    </answer>
</example>






<example xml:id="ex-lincombalgebra1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            If possible, express <m>[7, 4, -5]</m> as a linear combination of <m>[1,-2,1]</m> and <m>[3, 0, -1]</m>.
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            We are looking for coefficients <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that 

<me>
    a\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\\1\end{bmatrix}+b\begin{bmatrix}3\\0\\-1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}7\\4\\-5\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

This translates into a system of equations
<md>
    <mrow> a+3b\amp =7 </mrow>
    <mrow> -2a\amp =4 </mrow>
    <mrow> a-b\amp =-5 </mrow>
</md>
Solve this system for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, and enter your answers below:

<me>
    a=-2\quad\text{and}\quad b=3.
</me>

We conclude that <m>[7,4,-5]</m> is a linear combination of <m>[1,-2,1]</m> and <m>[3,0,-1]</m>, and write:

<me>
    \begin{bmatrix}7\\4\\-5\end{bmatrix}=-2\begin{bmatrix}1\\-2\\1\end{bmatrix}+3\begin{bmatrix}3\\0\\-1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
       </p>
    </answer>
</example>






<example xml:id="ex-lincombalgebra2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Set up a system of equations that can be used to express <m>[2,-1,3,0]</m> as a linear combination of 
            <m>[1,0,4,-2]</m>, <m>[-2,-1,1,-1]</m>, 
            <m>[0,4,-3,1]</m> and <m>[1,1,-1,4]</m>, 
            or to determine that such a combination does not exist.  
        </p>
        
        <p>
        <m> \textbf{Do not solve the system}. </m>
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            We are looking for <m>x_1</m>, <m>x_2</m>, <m>x_3</m> and <m>x_4</m> such that 

<me>
    x_1\begin{bmatrix}1\\0\\4\\-2\end{bmatrix}+x_2\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-1\\1\\-1\end{bmatrix}+x_3\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\\-3\\1\end{bmatrix}+x_4\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\-1\\4\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\-1\\3\\0\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

This translates into the following system of equations:


<me>
    \begin{array}{ccccccccc}
      x_1 \amp  -\amp 2x_2 \amp  \amp  \amp + \amp  x_4\amp = \amp 2 \\
        \amp  \amp -x_2  \amp + \amp 4x_3 \amp  +\amp  x_4\amp = \amp -1 \\
      4x_1 \amp + \amp x_2 \amp  -\amp 3x_3 \amp -\amp x_4\amp = \amp 3\\
	 -2x_1\amp  -\amp x_2 \amp  +\amp x_3\amp +\amp 4x_4\amp =\amp 0
    \end{array}.
</me>
       </p>
    </answer>
</example>
</subsection>














































<subsection xml:id="Section-Span">
    <title>The Linear Span</title>



<p>
    Recall that a vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is said to be a linear combination of vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots, \mathbf{v}_n</m> if one has
<me>
    \mathbf{v}=a_1\mathbf{v}_1+ a_2\mathbf{v}_2+\ldots + a_n\mathbf{v}_n
</me>

for some scalars <m>a_1, a_2, \ldots ,a_n</m>.
</p>


<p> 
We provide an explicit with explicit, concrete, numbers to demystify the above.
</p> 

<example xml:id="ex-spanintro">
    <statement>
        <p>
            If possible, express the given vector as a linear combination of 
<me>
    \mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix},\quad\mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
  Interpret your results geometrically.

  <ol>
  <li xml:id="item-spanintro1">
  <p> 
  
<me>
\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\5\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
</p>
</li>


  
  
  <li xml:id="item-spanintro2">
  <p> 
  
<me>
\mathbf{w}=\begin{bmatrix}5\\5\\1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>
</p>
</li>
 

  </ol>
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
           For <xref ref="item-spanintro1"/>, we need to find coefficients <m>a_1</m> and <m>a_2</m> such that <m>\mathbf{u}=a_1\mathbf{v}_1+a_2\mathbf{v}_2</m>. 
           To do this we need to solve the vector equation:
  
<me>
    a_1\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix}+a_2\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\5\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

  This equation translates into the following system:
  
  
<me>
    \begin{array}{ccccc}
      -2a_1 \amp  +\amp 2a_2\amp = \amp 2 \\
        -3a_1\amp  +\amp 3a_2\amp = \amp 3 \\
      4a_1 \amp + \amp 2a_2\amp = \amp 5\\
	     \end{array}.
</me>

  We write the system in augmented matrix form and apply elementary row operations to bring it to reduced row-echelon form.
  
<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 -2\amp 2\amp 2\\-3\amp 3\amp 3\\4\amp 2\amp 5
 \end{array}\right]\rightsquigarrow\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 1\amp 0\amp 1/2\\0\amp 1\amp 3/2\\0\amp 0\amp 0
 \end{array}\right].
</me>

  
  This shows that <m>a_1=\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>a_2=\frac{3}{2}</m>, and we can express <m>\mathbf{u}</m> as a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m>
   and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m> as follows:
  
<me>
    \frac{1}{2}\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix}+\frac{3}{2}\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\5\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

    
  Observe that because vector <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>, <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is the diagonal of a parallelogram whose sides are scalar multiples of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>. As such, <m>\mathbf{u}</m> lies in the same plane as <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>, as illustrated below.
</p>

<image width="80%">
   <shortdescription>Span of two vectors graphed</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
    \tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{130}
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
	\draw[-\gt ](-6,0,0)--(6,0,0) node[below left]{\(y\)};
    \draw[-\gt ](0,-2,0)--(0,8,0) node[below left]{\(z\)};
    \draw[-\gt ](0,0,-2)--(0,0,6) node[below left]{\(x\)};
    
    \filldraw[blue, opacity=0.3](0,0,0)--(4.5,3,3)--(3,5,2)--(-1.5,2,-1)--cycle;
    \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt,blue, -stealth](0,0,0)--(-3,4,-2)node[above left]{\(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix}\)};
    \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt,red, -stealth](0,0,0)--(3,2,2)node[right]{\(\mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}\)};
    \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt, -stealth](0,0,0)--(3,5,2)node[above]{\(\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\5\end{bmatrix}\)};
    
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>


  
  
<p> 
For <xref ref="item-spanintro2"/>, we need to solve the following vector equation:   
<me>
    a_1\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix}+a_2\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}5\\5\\1\end{bmatrix}.
</me>

  This equation corresponds to the system:
  
  
<me>
    \begin{array}{ccccc}
      -2a_1 \amp  +\amp 2a_2\amp = \amp 5 \\
        -3a_1\amp  +\amp 3a_2\amp = \amp 5 \\
      4a_1 \amp + \amp 2a_2\amp = \amp 1\\
	     \end{array}.
</me>

  Writing the system in augmented matrix form and applying elementary row operations gives us the following reduced row-echelon form:
  
<me>
    \left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 -2\amp 2\amp 5\\-3\amp 3\amp 5\\4\amp 2\amp 1
 \end{array}\right]\rightsquigarrow\left[\begin{array}{cc|c}  
 1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 1
 \end{array}\right].
</me>


 We conclude that there are no solutions, and <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is not a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.
 </p>
<p>
 Geometrically, this means that <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is not the diagonal of any parallelogram whose sides are scalar multiples of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  Thus, <m>\mathbf{w}</m> does not lie in the plane determined by <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  
</p>
 
 

<image width="80%">
   <shortdescription>Three vectors graphed without span</shortdescription>
    <latex-image>
        \tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{130}
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
	\draw[-\gt ](-6,0,0)--(6,0,0) node[below left]{\(y\)};
    \draw[-\gt ](0,-2,0)--(0,8,0) node[below left]{\(z\)};
    \draw[-\gt ](0,0,-2)--(0,0,6) node[below left]{\(x\)};
    
    
    \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt,blue, -stealth](0,0,0)--(-3,4,-2)node[above left]{\(\mathbf{v}_1=\begin{bmatrix}-2\\-3\\4\end{bmatrix}\)};
   
   \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt,red, -stealth](0,0,0)--(3,2,2)node[right]{\(\mathbf{v}_2=\begin{bmatrix}2\\3\\2\end{bmatrix}\)};
    
    \draw[-\gt , line width=2pt, -stealth](0,0,0)--(5,1,5)node[below]{\(\mathbf{w}=\begin{bmatrix}5\\5\\1\end{bmatrix}\)};

    \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
</image>
    </answer>
</example>


<p>
In <xref ref="item-spanintro1"/> of <xref ref="ex-spanintro"/> we expressed <m>\mathbf{u}</m> as a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>, 
and concluded that <m>\mathbf{u}</m> lies in the plane determined by <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  
We say that <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is <term>in the span</term> of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  
In fact, every vector in the plane determined by <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m> is in the span of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  
We say that <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m> <term>span the plane</term>.
</p>

<p>
In contrast, vector <m>\mathbf{w}</m> of <xref ref="item-spanintro2"/> of <xref ref="ex-spanintro"/> is not a linear combination of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.  We say that <m>\mathbf{w}</m> is not in the span of <m>\mathbf{v}_1</m> and <m>\mathbf{v}_2</m>.
</p>

<p>
The following video takes another look at <xref ref="ex-spanintro"/> using our new vocabulary.
</p>

<video youtube="Sum3qoOEXhY" play-at="select"/>





<definition xml:id="def-span">

    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p</m> be vectors in <m>\R^n</m>.  The set <m>S</m> of all linear combinations of <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p</m> is called the <term>span</term> of <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p</m>.  We write 

<me>
    S=\text{span}(\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p),
</me>

and we say that vectors <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p</m> <term>span</term> <m>S</m>.  Any vector in <m>S</m> is said to be <term>in the span</term> of <m>\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p</m>.  
The set <m>\{\mathbf{v}_1, \mathbf{v}_2,\ldots ,\mathbf{v}_p\}</m> is called a <term>spanning set</term> for the space <m>S</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>


<p>
The definition is rather formal even with all the preceding examples and geometric intuition. Running through the examples below in detail is highly recommended.
</p> 

<example xml:id="ex-describespan">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Describe <me>
                \text{span}\left(\begin{bmatrix}-3\\1\end{bmatrix}\right).
            </me>
       </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            The span of <m>[-3,1]</m> is the set of all linear combinations of <m>[-3,1]</m>.  
            Since we are looking for linear combinations of only one vector, we are really looking for all of its scalar multiples.  
            So, the span will be the set of all vectors of the form <m>\mathbf{v}=a[-3,1]</m>.  
            All such vectors lie on the line determined by <m>[-3,1]</m>.
        </p>

